		<div class="entry-content"><div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><div class="thumb"><img alt="Disunion" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/opinionator/disunion/disunion45.gif" width="50" height="50"></div><p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/disunion/">Disunion</a> follows the Civil War as it unfolded.</p></div></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/14/the-valentines-day-treaty/" data-title="Disunion: The Valentine&#8217;s Day Treaty" data-description="Could Elijah Steele&#039;s 1864 vision for settler-Indian compromise in the Pacific Northwest have averted the Indian Wars?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Elijah Steele knew he wasn&#8217;t authorized to negotiate an Indian treaty. As a lawyer, a judge, a former Wisconsin state senator, a founding settler of Siskiyou County, Calif., and the agent of Indian affairs for the Northern District of California, he was well aware of the protocols established by the United States Constitution. But Washington, D.C., was far away, and the nation was in the grip of civil war. And besides, on Feb. 14, 1864, Valentineâs Day, several hundred Klamath Basin Indians, much to his surprise, were camped outside his home in Yreka.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Steeleâs guests â Lileks of the Klamath, Schonchin of the Modoc and Josh and Jack of the Shasta Indian tribes, as well as others â wanted him to help negotiate a settlement among themselves and with the ever growing number of settlers pouring into the region. In fact, by the winter of 1864, against the backdrop of intense battles and increasing death tolls to the east, with Gen. William T. Shermanâs Army of the Mississippi tearing up railroad ties on its way to Meridian, Miss., rumors of an impending war between Indians and settlers reverberated through southern Oregon and northern California&#8217;s Klamath Basin.<span id="more-151934"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Steele knew he had to do something. And he did: The unauthorized agreement he helped forge brought peace, and offered an alternative vision of United States-Indian relations in the region. But it was a vision that wouldn&#8217;t last. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Settler-Indian violence was nothing new in Siskiyou County. Between 1847 and 1858, the Oregon and Washington Territories had been destabilized by a series of bloody wars, while farther to the south, in the gold fields of California, murder and mayhem reigned. This period of violence transformed the lives of the region&#8217;s Native Americans. Most Indians west of the Cascades were removed to distant or marginal reservations. Indians in California, though, suffered disproportionately. Scholars estimate that some 80 percent of the Indians in the state died from violence or the impact of displacement during the upheaval following the Gold Rush. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The flood of settlers into the region also altered its economics. Whereas before, Klamath Basin Indians trafficked in obsidian and enslaved Native Americans with their neighbors to the north, the establishment of cities and towns like Yreka redirected and integrated native people into an emerging, sedentary labor market. Indigenous women, some of whom were enslaved, sometimes worked as prostitutes and domestic laborers. Indigenous men found employment on ranches and farms as wage laborers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But this new, emerging economy raised other problems. The growth of American settlements on the eve of the Civil War accentuated the question of Indian land ownership in the region. As early as August 1854, the superintendent of Indian affairs for Oregon, Joel Palmer, visited the Klamath, and the two sides &#8220;contemplated negotiations for the extinguishment of the Indian title to the country.&#8221; But nothing came of it. There was less demand for the actual land than for safe passage for settlers through it. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Soon, rather than negotiating, officials in the Department of Indian Affairs were calling on the War Department to establish a military post in the region. In spring 1860, the Army responded â sort of. A detachment of 68 men traveled from Fort Umpqua on the Oregon coast to the Klamath Basin to establish a military presence. In July, those troops erected the short-lived Camp Day. But the Army soon abandoned the site. And calls for a more permanent military presence in the area fell on deaf ears. But there was little doubt that, sometime soon, another Indian war would erupt.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Dakota War of 1862 changed all that. After a summer of fighting the Dakotas in Minnesota, with hundreds of soldiers and settlers dead, and the execution of 38 Dakota prisoners â 303 were originally sentenced to hang â the War Department reassessed the prospect of another Indian war in the midst of an already exhausting civil war. Prevention seemed prudent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Meanwhile, local settlers in the Klamath Basin took advantage of the situation and stoked fears of Indian attacks. The Oregon Sentinel claimed that on average &#8220;28 whites [were] killed each year&#8221; by Klamath Basin Indians. This time the propaganda worked. In March 1863, Lt. Colonel Charles Drew traveled from Camp Baker near Jacksonville and established Fort Klamath. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fears of an Indian attack were overblown, but not unfounded. Although the Klamath Basin was distant from the battlegrounds of the Civil War, Indians there were aware of the strain the conflict placed on American resolve and resources. In the summer of 1863, two Modoc men, Skookum John and Tyee George, hatched a plan to use the war as an opportunity to ally the regionâs Indians against encroaching settlers. Their plot was the manifestation of everything settlers feared, and the Army responded with force: Colonel Drew arrested and executed Tyee George. And in November 1863, some of his troops killed Skookum John. They claimed he was resisting arrest. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dreams of expelling American settlement from the region died with Skookum John and Tyee George. But negotiation, the Indians realized, was still possible. And so when the Klamath Basin Indian headmen negotiated with Steele on Valentineâs Day 1864, they sought to defuse this tumultuous situation while preserving and strengthening their place in the region&#8217;s new political and economic landscape. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Their plan required a series of calculated compromises. Lileks, Schonchin and the other headmen agreed to live in peace and friendship with one another and with all settlers in the region. They also allowed settlers passage through their country. They agreed not to drink alcohol or steal from settlers and to carry weapons only for hunting or when bringing them to towns for repair. And they agreed to end the Indian slave trade and accept a ban on prostitution. </p>
<div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry">
<h6 class="kicker">Related</h6>
<h5><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2010/10/29/opinion/20101029-civil-war.html">Disunion Highlights</a></h5>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><img class="w75" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2010/11/08/opinion/civil-war-sumter75/civil-war-sumter75-popup.jpg" alt="Fort Sumter" /></p>
<p class="summary">Explore multimedia from the series and navigate through past posts, as well as photos and articles from the Times archive.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2010/10/29/opinion/20101029-civil-war.html">See the Highlights Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In exchange for these stipulations, the headmen reserved important rights: Their people would not be confined to a reservation; they could travel freely to visit other settlements; and they could charge fees for their labor â including the right to charge for particular tasks, including serving as guides. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The treaty was, taken together, a compromise â certainly not everything the Indians wanted, but it achieved their goals of protecting their property rights and maintaining their access to wage labor. &#8220;I have faith to believe that this conference has saved the country a bloody war,&#8221; Steele wrote when he transmitted the proposed treaty to the commissioner of Indian Affairs, William Dole, in Washington, D.C. &#8220;I hope that my act in the premises will meet with approval.&#8221; </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It did not. Opposition to the proposed treaty emerged straightaway. Commissioner Dole rejected it. Congress never considered it. Instead, they made available $10,000 to negotiate a new treaty, one that would extinguish Native American land rights in the region and establish a reservation. Negotiated in October 1864, this second treaty included few of the protections Klamath Basin Indians had sought from Steele. Left unfulfilled by the federal government for almost six years â another casualty of the congressional distractions that characterized Andrew Johnson&#8217;s presidency â this agreement festered and laid the foundation for years of conflict, ending in the Modoc War of 1872-73, one of the costliest Indian conflicts in American history.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In negotiating the Valentineâs Day Treaty of 1864, Steele and the Klamath Basin Indian headmen envisioned a future in which settlers and Indians would compromise, in which Native Americans would be integrated into the emerging economic systems of the West rather than segregated on isolated reservations. The failure of that vision in the face of Washington opposition, however, paved the way for the horrors of the Indian Wars that dominated the postwar West.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Follow Disunion at <a href="https://www.twitter.com/NYTcivilwar/">twitter.com/NYTcivilwar</a> or join us <a href="//www.facebook.com/pages/Civil-War-The-New-York-Times/171184126228555">on Facebook</a>.</em></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Sources: Lt. Colonel Charles Drew, &#8220;Official Report of the Owyhee Reconnaissance&#8221;; A. G. Walling, &#8220;History of Southern Oregon&#8221;; Hubert Howe Bancroft, &#8220;California Inter Pocula&#8221;; Keith Murray, &#8220;The Modoc and their War&#8221;; Andrew C. Isenberg, &#8220;Mining California: An Ecological History.&#8221; The author thanks C. Joseph Genetin-Pilawa and Ari Kelman for their insightful suggestions.</em></p>
<div class="w50 left"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/14/opinion/boyd-cothran/boyd-cothran-blogSmallThumb.jpg" alt="Boyd Cothran" /></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Boyd Cothran is an assistant professor of United States Indigenous and cultural history at York University in Toronto, Ontario, and the author of the forthcoming book &#8220;The Modoc War and the Making of American Innocence.â </em></p>
